[{"id":"/sicpy/2.2.2","tag":"TITLE","body":"2.2.2  \n    Hierarchical Structures"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p1","child":[{"body":"\n    The representation of sequences in terms of linked lists generalizes naturally to\n    represent sequences whose elements may themselves be sequences.  For\n    example, we can regard the object\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":" [[1, [2, None]], [3, [4, None]]] \t  "},{"body":"\n    constructed by\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":1,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgDgQwJYBOAFADYl4DOALkQIwA0SAlI2ZTQMyMAsTTQA","body":"pair(llist(1, 2), llist(3, 4)) "},{"body":"\n    as a linked list of three items, the first of which is itself a linked list,\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"[1, [2, None]]"},{"body":".\n\tFigure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.5","href":"/sicpy/2.2.2#fig-2.5"},{"body":"\n    shows the representation of this structure in terms of pairs.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"70%","src":"img_javascript/ch2-Z-G-15.svg","id":"#fig-2.5","captionHref":"/sicpy/2.2.2#fig-2.5","captionName":"Figure 2.5 ","captionBody":[{"body":"Structure formed by\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"pair(llist(1, 2), llist(3, 4))"},{"body":".\n          ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p2","child":[{"body":"\n    Another way to think of sequences whose elements are sequences is as\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"trees","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":".  The elements of the sequence are the branches of the\n    tree, and elements that are themselves sequences are subtrees.\n    Figure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.6","href":"/sicpy/2.2.2#fig-2.6"},{"body":"\n    shows the structure in\n    \n\tfigure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.5","href":"/sicpy/2.2.2#fig-2.5"},{"body":"\n    viewed as a tree.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"70%","src":"img_javascript/ch2-Z-G-16.svg","id":"#fig-2.6","captionHref":"/sicpy/2.2.2#fig-2.6","captionName":"Figure 2.6 ","captionBody":[{"body":"The linked-list structure in\n\t  figure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.5","href":"/sicpy/2.2.2#fig-2.5"},{"body":" viewed as a tree.\n          ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p3","child":[{"body":"\n    Recursion\n    \n    is a natural tool for dealing with tree structures, since we can\n    often reduce operations on trees to operations on their branches, which\n    reduce in turn to operations on the branches of the branches, and so on,\n    until we reach the leaves of the tree. As an example, compare the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":"function\n    of section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.2.1","href":"/sicpy/2.2.1"},{"body":" with the\n     ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_leaves"},{"body":"function,\n    which returns the total number of leaves of a tree:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":2,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgHiAvCABwEMBLAJwAoAbKkgZwBcKBGAGiQEp2b6mBmdgBYOHIA","body":"x = pair(llist(1, 2), llist(3, 4)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":3,"eval":true,"prependLength":7,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgJgUwGYgA2OAdgOYAuAFgBQCWFOAtgM4CUAXOiDyAE44KAVz4kQNAAwg6BOiwD6JAPYkc9RqzbdeOnTkIscIAIwgA1EVKVaFAIZ1C65uzZb0ADxABeEAAd7fDSEhHIUNMYANEhsUcGhNADMUQAsrpi+fHQkYcTk1DTurkA","body":"print(length(x)) ","output":"3"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":4,"eval":true,"prependLength":8,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgHiAvCABwEMBLAJwAoAbKkgZwBcKBGAGiQEp2b6mBmdgBYOHTABMApgDMQAYwD2AVwB2DAPpUJRAG4S6FLBwBc6EGZBkJDRWWUgKABhAkZ9NcvnKJB0eb-+JKjoJEGZnGQ8GZzo1YnIfU38kwOC5JVUNLV19AAstMR8OEABqNJV1TR09CgZSKkLRdAIyElUKBXLMqv1DDiA","body":"print(count_leaves(x)) ","output":"4"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":5,"eval":true,"prependLength":7,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgJgUwGYgA2OAdgOYAuAFgBQCWFOAtgM4CUAXOiDyAE44KAVz4kQNAAwg6BOiwD6JAPYkc9RqzbdeOnTkIscIAIwgA1EVKVaFAIZ1C65uzZb0ADxABeEAAd7fDSEhHIUNMYANEhsUcGhNADMUQAsrpi+fHQkFPJxLGF5Ye5R7q5AA","body":"print_llist(llist(x, x)) ","output":"llist(llist(llist(1, 2), 3, 4), llist(llist(1, 2), 3, 4))"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":6,"eval":true,"prependLength":7,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgJgUwGYgA2OAdgOYAuAFgBQCWFOAtgM4CUAXOiDyAE44KAVz4kQNAAwg6BOiwD6JAPYkc9RqzbdeOnTkIscIAIwgA1EVKVaFAIZ1C65uzZb0ADxABeEAAd7fDSEhHIUNMYANEhsUcGhNADMUQAsrpi+fHQkYcTk1EEhLGHuUe6ubEA","body":"print(length(llist(x, x))) ","output":"2"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":7,"eval":true,"prependLength":8,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgHiAvCABwEMBLAJwAoAbKkgZwBcKBGAGiQEp2b6mBmdgBYOHTABMApgDMQAYwD2AVwB2DAPpUJRAG4S6FLBwBc6EGZBkJDRWWUgKABhAkZ9NcvnKJB0eb-+JKjoJEGZnGQ8GZzo1YnIfU38kwOC5JVUNLV19AAstMR8OEABqNJV1TR09CgZSKkLRdAIyElUKBXLMqv0eRgN2QxEgA","body":"print(count_leaves(llist(x, x))) ","output":"8"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p4","child":[{"body":"\n    To implement\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_leaves"},{"body":",\n      \n    recall the recursive plan for computing\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":":","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"The ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":"\n\tof a linked list","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":" is 1 plus\n\tthe ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":"\n\tof the\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n\tof ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":".\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"The ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":"\n\tof the empty linked list is 0.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"The function\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_leaves"},{"body":"\n    is similar.  The value for the empty linked list is the same:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_leaves"},{"body":"\n\tof the empty linked list is 0.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n    But in the reduction step, where we strip off the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"\n    of the linked list, we must take into account that the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"\n    may itself be a tree whose leaves we need to count.  Thus, the appropriate\n    reduction step is\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_leaves"},{"body":"\n\tof a tree ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":" is\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_leaves"},{"body":"\n\tof the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"\n\tof ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":" plus\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_leaves"},{"body":"\n\tof the\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"\n\tof ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":".\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n    Finally, by taking\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"s\n    we reach actual leaves, so we need another base case:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"count_leaves"},{"body":"\n\tof a leaf is 1.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n    To aid in writing recursive\n    functions\n    on trees,\n    our Python environment\n    provides the primitive predicate\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"is_pair"},{"body":",\n    which tests whether its argument is a pair. Here is the complete\n    function:","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-1","body":"1","href":"/sicpy/2.2.2#footnote-1"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":8,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgJgUwGYgDGA9gK4B2ALgPoA2OAhgG44DOAFAB4CUAXOiEEgATjkqlh5EOwAMIAJYF5rauWLkcXbgKG7dOWqxwgAjAoJrKClQAcG84Vp169Bo0TJU6jFhwAWjFha3CAA1B4UNPTMbOyU9rTB2ug2wvJU7CSR3jEcdg7stLTKlOwmADRI3JVFJewAzJUALNyt3EA","body":"def count_leaves(x):\n    return (0 if is_none(x)\n            else 1 if not is_pair(x)\n            else count_leaves(head(x)) + count_leaves(tail(x))) "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.24","id":"#ex-2.24","child":[{"body":"\n    Suppose we evaluate the expression\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"llist(1, llist(2, llist(3, 4)))"},{"body":".\n      \n    Give the result printed by the interpreter, the corresponding\n    box-and-pointer structure, and the interpretation of this as a tree (as in\n    figure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.6","href":"/sicpy/2.2.2#fig-2.6"},{"body":").","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":9,"eval":false,"body":"[1, [[2, [[3, [4, None]], None]], None]]"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"70%","src":"img_javascript/ch2-Z-G-ex-2-24.svg","id":"#fig-"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"70%","src":"img_javascript/ch2-Z-G-ex-2-24-tree.svg","id":"#fig-"}]}]}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.25","id":"#ex-2.25","child":[{"body":"\n    Give combinations of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"head"},{"body":"s\n    and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"tail"},{"body":"s\n    that will pick 7 from each of the following\n    linked lists, given in linked-list notation:","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":10,"eval":false,"body":"llist(1, 3, llist(5, 7), 9)\n\nllist(llist(7))\n\nllist(1, llist(2, llist(3, llist(4, llist(5, llist(6, 7))))))"}],"solution":[{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":11,"eval":false,"body":"head(tail(head(tail(tail(the_first_list)))))"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":12,"eval":false,"body":"head(head(the_second_list))"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":13,"eval":false,"body":"head(tail(head(tail(head(tail(head(tail(head(\n    tail(head(tail(the_third_list))))))))))))"}]}]}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.26","id":"#ex-2.26","child":[{"body":"\n    Suppose we define ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":" and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"y"},{"body":" to be two linked lists:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":14,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgHiAvCAGwIEsBnAFwAoBGAGiXoGYBKTBfIsqgFnoFZ6ANmZA","body":"x = llist(1, 2, 3)\n\ny = llist(4, 5, 6) "},{"body":"\n        What is the result of evaluating each of the\n        following expressions, in box notation and linked-list notation?\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":15,"eval":true,"prependLength":9,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgJgUwGYgCGADsTgHZYAUANgJYDOALgIwA0I9ziAlAFzoQQkACccTAK4jyIWoyaIQdAowD65APbkcc5ix6DhRozhoMcIYoToiqACxyFqXVjw4kylKk2s1drjhdeHgN0AA8QAF5OFyp2JA4AZlCEaJpYgBYOAFYOADZQjwpqMI44HiA","body":"append(x, y) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":16,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgHiAvCAGwIEsBnAFwAoBGAGiXoGYBKTBfIsqgFnoFZ6ANlboADgENiAJ0pZ6cZkA","body":"pair(x, y) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":17,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgHiAvCAGwIEsBnAFwAoBGAGiXoGYBKTBfIsqgFnoFZ6ANlbpOFSlnpxmQA","body":"llist(x, y) "}],"solution":[{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":18,"eval":true,"prependLength":11,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniATAOhYgUOgJgUwGYgCGADsTgHZYAUANgJYDOALgIwA0I9ziAlAFzoQQkACcc